[Dealing with elephant carcasses is always a problem, frequently exacerbated by the absence of adequate firewood or liquid fuels. Burning infected carcasses is normally the optimum decision in livestock and game outbreaks. Some have recommended covering elephant carcasses with thorn brush to discourage scavengers. Putrefaction with the normal acidification of the carcass tissues that accompanies it will rapidly kill the vegetative organisms. So the environmental contamination around an unopened carcass may be relatively modest. - Mod.MHJ

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2494227,18255.]
